Bill Ackman, the prolific X poster and hedge fund billionaire, has
proposed a deal to position himself as his generation=E2=80=99s answer to W=
arren Buffett=E2=80=94his latest attempt to secure a place on Wall Street=
=E2=80=99s Mount Rushmore.

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Ever since I met the flamboyant hedge fund manager Bill
Ackman 12 years ago, in his office above the Brooklyn Diner on West 57th St=
reet=E2=80=94fresh off his infamous CNBC feud with Carl Icahn=E2=80=94he=E2=
=80=99s touted his admiration for, and similarity to, the legendary investo=
r Warren Buffett. Of course, the comparison was more than a little off. But=
 Bill is Bill, with no shortage of ego. At 58, he still thinks of himself a=
s his generation=E2=80=99s Buffett, who is still kicking it at 94 with a ne=
t worth of $140 billion=E2=80=94more than 300
positions above Ackman on the Bloomberg leaderboard.

Lately, I=E2=80=99ve been wondering what motivates Bill to keep pressing hi=
s advantage. He=E2=80=99s worth about $8 billion these days. He=E2=80=99s b=
een a fiend on X, where he=E2=80=99s more prolific than ever. He=E2=80=99s =
all in on the Trump-Elon show. He=E2=80=99s taken the wood to Business Insi=
der over what it wrote about his wife, Neri Oxman. Last year, he took down =
Claudine
Gay, the president of Harvard, his alma mater, and gets some credit for tak=
ing down three other Ivy League presidents, to boot.

=C2=A0

Then, on Monday, Bill announced his most explicit effort yet to turn himsel=
f into the Gen X Buffett. Naturally, I called him up to discuss what turned=
 out to be a somewhat convoluted, rather diabolical deal proposal. Simply p=
ut: Bill wants to turn the Howard Hughes
Corporation=E2=80=94a publicly traded real estate developer in which Ackman=
 and his affiliated entities own a 38 percent stake=E2=80=94into his own ve=
rsion of Berkshire Hathaway, Buffett=E2=80=99s publicly traded investment v=
ehicle which was once a forlorn textile company. Howard Hughes, Ackman told=
 me on Monday, is =E2=80=9Ca lot better than a crappy textile company, righ=
t? It=E2=80=99s actually a really good business. And it=E2=80=99s going to =
become a lot more cash-flow positive over the next decade, and we can just =
redeploy that
capital.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Ackman=E2=80=99s idea is to increase his stake in Howard Hughes to at least=
 61 percent (but not more than 69.2 percent) through a combination of a new=
 $1 billion investment from himself and his partners, and a simultaneous $5=
00 million corporate share repurchase plan. That would make Howard Hughes a=
 publicly traded company that=E2=80=99s able to do what Berkshire Hathaway =
does: acquire other companies,
public and private; buy stakes in other companies, public and private; issu=
e new debt and equity securities as needed to bolster his access to capital=
 (though Buffett does not issue new equity); and harvest what Bill hopes wi=
ll be the output of Howard Hughes=E2=80=99 cash-generating machine. He=E2=
=80=99s offering to bolster his stake from existing shareholders for $85 pe=
r share, which he claims is a 38 percent premium to the =E2=80=9Cunaffected=
=E2=80=9D share price of Howard Hughes, before he started making noise abou=
t doing
something with the company. Shareholders can either take their pro rata sha=
re of the $85 in cash, or hold on to their stock and join the Bill Ackman s=
leighride.

=C2=A0

It=E2=80=99s not all that dissimilar to what the Ellisons and RedBird Capit=
al have proposed in their still-pending acquisition of Paramount Global: ge=
tting control of the company but leaving it public, and giving investors a =
choice to cash
out (at least in part) or stick around as the company goes in a new directi=
on. Of course, the Ellisons and RedBird=E2=80=99s Gerry Cardinale aren=E2=
=80=99t making a bid to claim the crown of the Oracle of Omaha.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Bill told me that he came up with his devilish idea while sitting on the be=
ach over Christmas, and that he started writing his 14-page offer letter to=
 the Howard Hughes board of directors
this past Saturday at 4:55 a.m. Over the past few days, the Hughes board ha=
s set up a special committee to consider Ackman=E2=80=99s offer, and hired =
legal advisors and Morgan Stanley to evaluate the proposal. His first commu=
nication with the special committee was on Monday.

=C2=A0

What Would Buffett Do?
----------------------

In our conversation, Bill told me that the Howard Hughes proposal
was born out of his frustration with how the company has performed in the p=
ublic markets ever since he spun it out 14 years ago from another company h=
e owned=E2=80=94General Growth Properties=E2=80=94and on which he made a ki=
lling, buying its distressed bonds and converting them into equity in the c=
ompany. He kept hoping Howard Hughes would trade better as a public company=
, even as he kept narrowing its focus. At one point, in 2019, he ran a proc=
ess to sell the company, but no one showed up to buy it.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Howard Hughes used to own the South Street Seaport, for instance. Bill thou=
ght, when he spun off that landmark property last year, that the company=E2=
=80=99s stock would trade up. Instead, it traded down. =E2=80=9CWe really w=
orked hard to refine it and make it into an amazing, interesting business,=
=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CAnd I think it really is an amazing and inte=
resting business, but it=E2=80=99s never caught on in Wall Street land.=E2=
=80=9D

=C2=A0

The disconnect between Bill=E2=80=99s appraisal of the stock and the market=
=E2=80=99s valuation of it got him thinking. As he explained last year on L=
ex Fridman=E2=80=99s podcast, =E2=80=9CMost of what I=E2=80=99ve learned in=
 the investment business I=E2=80=99ve learned from Warren Buffett. He=E2=80=
=99s been my great professor of this business.=E2=80=9D And the number one =
lesson Ackman took from his idol: =E2=80=9CWhen the lemmings are running ov=
er the cliff, that=E2=80=99s
the time where you=E2=80=99re facing the other direction and you=E2=80=99re=
 running in the other direction. =E2=80=A6 You have to get excited when thi=
ngs get cheaper.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Anyway, given all the cash Bill made from owning General Growth, he=E2=80=
=99s really just been playing with house money with Howard Hughes. So he de=
cided he should just buy the rest of the company. Last August, he filed a 1=
3D to telegraph his intentions. He hired
Jefferies, the investment bank, and talked to the other investors in the co=
mpany. He said they told him, We kind of wanted to invest with you in this =
thing, and you=E2=80=99re taking it private. Is there any way you could lea=
ve part of it public, so we can go along for the ride? That=E2=80=99s when =
he hatched the plan to keep Howard Hughes public but take greater control o=
f it, and use it as his new, shiny, Berkshire-like investment vehicle. (He =
says he hasn=E2=80=99t spoken with Buffett about his
proposal.)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Ackman=E2=80=99s plan would leave existing Howard Hughes management in plac=
e at the operating level, and create a holding company above it to redeploy=
 the cash generated by Howard Hughes in the way Bill wants. He=E2=80=99d be=
 C.E.O. of the holding company, and put his hedge fund=E2=80=99s management=
 team in place around him to sift through investment opportunities and mana=
ge that business.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

He won=E2=80=99t be working for free, of course. He intends to charge Howar=
d Hughes an annual management fee, paid quarterly, of 1.5 percent of the co=
mpany=E2=80=99s equity value. Right now, with Howard Hughes=E2=80=99s marke=
t value at $4 billion, Ackman=E2=80=99s annual fee would be $60 million. Th=
at number would increase along with the company=E2=80=99s equity value. At =
that price, Bill thinks, the company would be getting him at a bargain.

=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CThe Chutzpah=E2=80=9D
------------------

Bill told me he=E2=80=99ll never sell his stake in Howard Hughes
if he pulls off this new deal. I wondered how committing up front not to se=
ll would work out for him and his investors. After all, Bill does need liqu=
idity. Not surprisingly, however, it turns out he has a master plan, and th=
e Howard Hughes deal is part of it.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Back in June, you=E2=80=99ll remember, Bill sold a 10 percent stake in Pers=
hing Square Capital Management, his management company, for $1.05
billion, valuing the company at $10.5 billion. Among the new investors were=
 Arch Capital Group and Menora Mivtachim, an Israeli insurance company. The=
 management company is owned by Bill (44 percent), 17 of his partners at Pe=
rshing (another 46 percent), and the new outside investors. His intention i=
s to take Pershing Square Capital Management public this year, with the hop=
e that it will increase in value. He=E2=80=99d continue to own his big chun=
k of Howard Hughes, along with a big chunk of Pershing
Square Holdings=E2=80=94his publicly traded European investment vehicle=E2=
=80=94as well as his U.S. hedge fund and its equity investments in a variet=
y of companies. If he needs (or wants) liquidity, he can sell more of the n=
ewly-public management company, which he=E2=80=99s calling Pershing Square =
Inc.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, the Howard Hughes deal is far from done. The special committee h=
as to do its thing and then recommend the deal
(or not). At least one investor, Jonathan Boyar, has written to the board o=
pposing Ackman=E2=80=99s takeover. =E2=80=9C[T]he chutzpah required to prop=
ose such a lowball offer, while positioning it as a benefit to shareholders=
, cannot be ignored,=E2=80=9D he wrote, urging the special committee to rej=
ect the offer.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Howard Hughes stock was up 10 percent on Monday after Bill announced his de=
al. =E2=80=9CThe other fun
thing here is, we=E2=80=99re not starting out with a $100 billion market ca=
p or a $25 billion market cap,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re =
starting out with a company with a $4 billion market cap, right? It=E2=80=
=99s a lot easier to compound $4 billion into a very big number. Buffett co=
mplains about all the money he=E2=80=99s lugging around. That=E2=80=99s why=
 [he=E2=80=99s] got $350 billion sitting in cash.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Bill pines for the day he might be mentioned in the same
breath as the Oracle of Omaha. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s fun,=E2=80=9D he said.=
 =E2=80=9CWhen I launched Gotham Partners, my first fund, I said, =E2=80=98=
My goal is to have a better record than Buffett.=E2=80=99 Each year, he kee=
ps extending out the record. Each year, I=E2=80=99ve got to work again. He =
keeps moving out the horizon.=E2=80=9D In the meantime, Bill will keep up t=
he chase.

