;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Ever since I met the flamboyant hedge fund=
 manager <strong>Bill
Ackman</strong> 12 years ago, in his office above the Brooklyn Diner on Wes=
t 57th Street=E2=80=94fresh off his infamous CNBC feud with <strong>Carl Ic=
ahn</strong>=E2=80=94he=E2=80=99s touted his admiration for, and similarity=
 to, the legendary investor <strong>Warren Buffett</strong>. Of course, the=
 comparison was more than a little off. But Bill is Bill, with no shortage =
of ego. At 58, he still thinks of himself as his generation=E2=80=99s Buffe=
tt, who is still kicking it at 94 with a net worth of $140 billion=E2=80=94=
more than 300
positions above Ackman on the Bloomberg leaderboard.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;"><br/>Lately, I=E2=80=99ve been wondering what motivat=
es Bill to keep pressing his advantage. He=E2=80=99s worth about $8 billion=
 these days. He=E2=80=99s been a fiend on X, where he=E2=80=99s more prolif=
ic than ever. He=E2=80=99s all in on the <strong>Trump</strong>-<strong>Elo=
n </strong>show. He=E2=80=99s taken the wood to Business Insider over what =
it wrote about his wife, <strong>Neri Oxman</strong>. Last year, he took do=
wn <strong>Claudine
Gay</strong>, the president of Harvard, his alma mater, and gets some credi=
t for taking down three other Ivy League presidents, to boot.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Then, on Monday, Bill announced his most explicit effort yet to tu=
rn himself into the Gen X Buffett. Naturally, I called him up to discuss wh=
at turned out to be a somewhat convoluted, rather diabolical deal proposal.=
 Simply put: Bill wants to turn the Howard Hughes
Corporation=E2=80=94a publicly traded real estate developer in which Ackman=
 and his affiliated entities own a 38 percent stake=E2=80=94into his own ve=
rsion of Berkshire Hathaway, Buffett=E2=80=99s publicly traded investment v=
ehicle which was once a forlorn textile company. Howard Hughes, Ackman told=
 me on Monday, is =E2=80=9Ca lot better than a crappy textile company, righ=
t? It=E2=80=99s actually a really good business. And it=E2=80=99s going to =
become a lot more cash-flow positive over the next decade, and we can just =
redeploy that
capital.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Ackman=E2=80=99s idea is to inc=
rease his stake in Howard Hughes to at least 61 percent (but not more than =
69.2 percent) through a combination of a new $1 billion investment from him=
self and his partners, and a simultaneous $500 million corporate share repu=
rchase plan. That would make Howard Hughes a publicly traded company that=
=E2=80=99s able to do what Berkshire Hathaway does: acquire other companies=
,
public and private; buy stakes in other companies, public and private; issu=
e new debt and equity securities as needed to bolster his access to capital=
 (though Buffett does not issue new equity); and harvest what Bill hopes wi=
ll be the output of Howard Hughes=E2=80=99 cash-generating machine. He=E2=
=80=99s offering to bolster his stake from existing shareholders for $85 pe=
r share, which he claims is a 38 percent premium to the =E2=80=9Cunaffected=
=E2=80=9D share price of Howard Hughes, before he started making noise abou=
t doing
something with the company. Shareholders can either take their pro rata sha=
re of the $85 in cash, or hold on to their stock and join the Bill Ackman s=
leighride.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It=E2=80=99s not all that dissimilar to wh=
at the <strong>Ellisons</strong> and RedBird Capital have proposed in their=
 still-pending acquisition of Paramount Global: getting control of the comp=
any but leaving it public, and giving investors a choice to cash
out (at least in part) or stick around as the company goes in a new directi=
on. Of course, the Ellisons and RedBird=E2=80=99s <strong>Gerry Cardinale</=
strong> aren=E2=80=99t making a bid to claim the crown of the Oracle of Oma=
ha.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Bill told me that he came up with his devilis=
h idea while sitting on the beach over Christmas, and that he started writi=
ng his 14-page offer letter to the Howard Hughes board of directors
this past Saturday at 4:55 a.m. Over the past few days, the Hughes board ha=
s set up a special committee to consider Ackman=E2=80=99s offer, and hired =
legal advisors and Morgan Stanley to evaluate the proposal. His first commu=
nication with the special committee was on Monday.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
">=C2=A0</p></div>
